diagnostic's draw budget and its wall-clock cost relative to the fit) are
attached at the top level.
\item \code{pareto_k_by_arm}, \code{pareto_k_by_arm_is_ess}, \code{pareto_k_by_arm_scope} —
present only with \code{control$diagnose_k = "by_arm"} (gcol33/tulpa#120).
Named (by arm) outer Pareto-\eqn{\hat{k}} restricted to each arm's
hyperparameter axes, the other arms held at their posterior mean, so a
tail-heavy joint k can be localised to one arm. A per-arm entry is \code{NA}
when that arm carries no varying axis. Each arm carries its own bootstrap
uncertainty: \code{pareto_k_by_arm_se_boot}, \code{pareto_k_by_arm_ci_low} /
\code{pareto_k_by_arm_ci_high}, \code{pareto_k_by_arm_se_formula},
\code{pareto_k_by_arm_tail_points} and \code{pareto_k_by_arm_band_confident}.
\item \code{k_quality_requested}, \code{k_quality_reached}, \code{k_quality_best},
\code{k_quality_reason} — the reliability verdict for the \code{control$k_quality}
intent (gcol33/tulpa#129). \code{k_quality_requested} echoes the intent;
\code{k_quality_best} is the band actually achieved (\code{"good"} / \code{"ok"} /
\code{"unreliable"}, or \code{"uncertain"} when the bootstrap CI crosses a boundary);
\code{k_quality_reached} is \code{TRUE}/\code{FALSE} for an \code{"ok"} / \code{"good"} target
(\code{NA} for \code{"report"} / \code{"none"}), never silently downgraded; and
\code{k_quality_reason} records why it stopped.
\item \code{adaptive_grid_info} — when \code{adaptive_grid = TRUE}, a list with
\code{triggered_axes} (character) and \code{n_points_added} (integer)
describing the refinement passes. NULL otherwise.
\item \code{prune_cheap_log_marginal}, \code{prune_mask}, \code{prune_n_pruned},
\code{prune_tol} — present only when \code{prune = TRUE} and the safety gate did
not fall back. Cheap-pass log-marginals at every cell, a logical mask
of pruned cells, the pruned-cell count, and the threshold actually
applied. Pruned cells have \code{log_marginal = -Inf} so they get zero
weight under \code{.nl_normalise_weights_safe}.
\item \code{prune_fallback_triggered}, \code{prune_fallback_reason} — present only when
the safety gate fell back to the full grid. The returned fit is the
full-grid (unpruned) result; the reason string records which gate
condition tripped.
}
}
\description{
Outer-grid nested Laplace driver for \emph{joint} models — multiple response
arms sharing one latent prior block, parameterized as a per-arm field
amplitude (sigma) on a unit-precision latent.

Supported priors:
\itemize{
\item \code{"bym2"}       — outer grid over \verb{(sigma, rho [, alpha])}.
Latent: \code{phi (n_s) | theta (n_s)} with unit-precision
ICAR + iid components.
\item \code{"icar"}       — outer grid over \code{(sigma [, alpha])}.
Latent: \code{phi (n_s)} with unit-precision ICAR.
\item \code{"car_proper"} — outer grid over \verb{(sigma, rho_car [, alpha])}.
Latent: \code{phi (n_s)} with \code{Q = D - rho_car * W}.
}

Other backends (NNGP, HSGP, RW1/2, AR1) follow the same interface and
land under Phase 3.
}
\section{(sigma, alpha) parameterization}{

Each arm's linear predictor reads
\deqn{\eta_{arm} = X_{arm} \beta_{arm} + \sigma_{arm} \cdot z_s,}
where \eqn{z_s} is a unit-precision latent (ICAR(tau=1) for ICAR/BYM2,
or the BYM2 mix; CAR_proper uses the structure of
\eqn{D - \rho_{car} W}). All arms share the donor amplitude
\eqn{\sigma} from the outer-grid \code{sigma_grid} axis. The copy arm's
amplitude is \eqn{\sigma_{arm} = \alpha \cdot \sigma}, where \eqn{\alpha}
is a direct outer-grid axis taken from \code{copy$alpha_grid}. The Cartesian
product is over \verb{(sigma, [rho/rho_car,] alpha[, phi])}. Direct \eqn{\alpha}
as an outer-grid axis (rather than a post-hoc ratio
\eqn{\alpha = \sigma_{pos} / \sigma_{occ}}) avoids plug-in bias on the
weakly-identified ratio at small \code{n_pos} and lets a regularizing
hyperprior land on \eqn{\alpha} directly.
}

\examples{
\donttest{
set.seed(1)
S <- 25L                                   # shared spatial units (chain graph)
nb <- lapply(seq_len(S), function(s) setdiff(c(s - 1L, s + 1L), c(0L, S + 1L)))
nn <- lengths(nb)
field <- as.numeric(scale(cumsum(rnorm(S, 0, 0.4))))
mk_arm <- function(m, fam) {
  si <- sample(S, m, replace = TRUE); x <- rnorm(m)
  lin <- 0.2 + 0.5 * x + 0.8 * field[si]
  y <- if (fam == "binomial") rbinom(m, 1L, plogis(lin)) else lin + rnorm(m, 0, 0.5)
  list(y = as.numeric(y), n_trials = rep(1L, m), X = cbind(1, x),
       spatial_idx = si, family = fam, phi = if (fam == "gaussian") 0.5 else 1)
}
prior <- list(type = "icar", n_spatial_units = S,
              adj_row_ptr = c(0L, cumsum(nn)), adj_col_idx = unlist(nb) - 1L,
              n_neighbors = nn, sigma_grid = c(0.3, 0.7, 1.4))
fit <- tulpa_nested_laplace_joint(
  responses = list(occ = mk_arm(200L, "binomial"), pos = mk_arm(200L, "gaussian")),
  prior = prior)
fit$theta_mean        # shared field amplitude, integrated across both arms
}
}
\references{
Rue, Martino & Chopin (2009). Approximate Bayesian inference for latent
Gaussian models by using integrated nested Laplace approximations.
\emph{JRSS-B} 71(2):319-392.
}
\seealso{
\code{\link[=tulpa_nested_laplace]{tulpa_nested_laplace()}} for the single-arm engine.
